Entering the Ruins 

Inside the pyramid, carvings show a civilization built on collective learning. Leaders teach instead of rule. Knowledge flows freely. Gods observe rather than dominate. 

The protagonist interprets this as validation of his Structural Order theory: they were not ruled  they were organized. 

Escape from the Cult – Turning Point 

Captured and dragged toward an altar, the protagonist awakens mid-transport. He strangles the cultist leading him. This decisive act reveals his will. 

Thoth recognizes his ideological alignment: he believes in structure, hierarchy, and correction. He is not passive. He is useful. 

Deeper Exploration – The Truth Shifts 

Further inside, the carvings reveal the civilization’s prosperity: minimal disease, rare conflict, intellectual advancement. 

However, darker inscriptions appear: 'The Unworthy cloud the collective mind.' 'Sacrifice is purification of imbalance.' 

The gods did not demand blind worship they demanded intellectual purity. 



Environmental Storytelling and Room Discoveries


Throughout the pyramid, Robert gathers information by observing murals, vases, stone tablets, and architectural elements left behind by the lost civilization. Each room reinforces his theory of structural order while gradually revealing the darker reality behind the system created by Thoth.

Many discoveries also unlock abilities through Robert’s journal, as the symbols he sketches become activated by Thoth’s influence.






Room I

The first chamber introduces evidence that confirms Robert’s theory while also presenting new mysteries.

The room contains several ceramic vases and fragments displaying patterns and symbols that do not match known Egyptian artistic traditions.

Upon examining them, Robert comments:

“Huh… Did another settlement live here? I don’t recall this kind of pattern.”

This suggests that the civilization hidden within the pyramid existed outside official historical records.

Large stone columns along the walls display carvings representing the structure of the civilization. These carvings illustrate three social layers:

Workers and citizens collaborating at the base

Scholars and scribes organizing knowledge in the middle

A single Scribe figure standing at the top

When Robert studies the carving he reacts with excitement:

“Yes… this is exactly what I’m looking for.”

To him, this appears to confirm his Three-Tier Structural Model.

However, subtle visual elements hint that the structure may have been more rigid and controlled than he initially believes.






Room II 

This room introduces the first direct interaction with Thoth.

At the center of the room stands a large statue of Thoth, surrounded by murals depicting people studying scrolls, tablets, and astronomical diagrams.

Robert remarks:

“So they were worshiping Thoth… interesting.”

By interacting with the mural, the player can observe different sections, prompting Robert’s analytical commentary:

“They were producing a lot of scrolls and tablets.”

“They were learning directly from Thoth.”

“Knowledge seems to have been central to their society.”

The mural contains numerous eye symbols, representing observation and knowledge.

When Robert studies these symbols, a whisper begins to form in his mind. The voice grows clearer and more assertive.

His journal suddenly updates, and a symbol forms within its pages, unlocking the Scan ability.

Robert reacts with confusion:

“Wha— what the hell?”

The whisper becomes slightly clearer:

“Use… powers… help… escape.”

This moment marks the beginning of Thoth’s influence.

Additionally, Robert notices strange markings appearing on his hand, resembling geometric tattoos connected to the symbols in his journal.

These marks indicate that Thoth has granted him abilities.




Puzzle – The Stone Tablets

Around the room are five stone tablets, each glowing faintly with different colors when scanned.

The player must place them in the correct order on the wall beside the door.

A blood-stained note from a previous researcher provides partial clues. Two tablet colors are circled, while the rest remain uncertain.

The note appears abruptly interrupted, suggesting the researcher was captured before finishing their work.

Once arranged correctly, the door opens.




Corridor – The Hopscotch Path

After leaving the room, the player enters a corridor filled with floor tiles that trigger deadly traps.

Using the Scan ability, Robert can reveal safe tiles while dangerous tiles remain dark.

The player must carefully navigate the path while scanning the environment.

This reinforces the idea that observation and knowledge are required for survival.






Room III 

Parts of this chamber are completely dark.

Robert initially cannot see anything within the shadows.

While exploring, he discovers a vase depicting scenes of Thoth teaching humans how to create fire.

The mural also shows people performing rituals in which knowledge and energy appear to flow toward Thoth.

After observing the vase, Robert gains the Fire ability, allowing him to create flame in his hand to illuminate dark areas.

This ability reveals hidden levers that must be activated to open the next door.

Robert begins to realize that the civilization’s advancements were not purely human achievements.





Puzzle – The Solar Clock

The room contains a large solar clock mechanism.

Three movable light sources and three levers control how light reflects across the chamber.

The player must align the light beams so they converge on a marked point on the ground.

When the beams align, a container opens revealing a decorated ceremonial vase, reinforcing the Fire ability.

Lighting all torches in the room reveals constellation patterns on the ceiling.

Using the Scan ability, the player can identify the correct constellation of Thoth and replicate it by connecting the glowing points.






Corridor – The Moon Maze

The next corridor becomes a maze of branching passages.

Some paths contain collapsing floor tiles and hidden spikes.

The player must use Fire to illuminate dark paths and Scan to reveal moon phase symbols on the walls.

These symbols indicate the correct direction to travel.





Room IV

After lighting two torches, the room becomes fully visible.

Murals depict the Scribe acting as mediator between Thoth and the people, delivering knowledge and maintaining order.

Another mural shows early engineering methods used to lift heavy stone blocks.

Studying the mural grants Robert the Telekinesis ability.






Puzzle – The Scales of Balance

The room contains several statues and a large set of scales.

Using Scan, the player identifies statues with matching colors.

Using Telekinesis, the player must place statues on the scales to balance their weight.

Once balanced, the door opens.






Corridor

The next corridor contains dart traps triggered by pressure plates.

The player must return to the previous room to find a vase that grants the Barrier ability.

The vase depicts Thoth teaching people to build defensive walls to protect their civilization.

Barrier allows the player to block the darts and pass through the corridor safely.





Room V 

This room contains a massive gap blocking the path forward.

Using Scan, the player identifies objects on the opposite side.

With Telekinesis, Robert pulls a vase from across the gap.

Studying it grants the Bridge ability, which allows him to create temporary paths across empty space.

The vase depicts Thoth teaching agriculture, symbolizing the building of civilization.






The Final Revelation

After crossing the gap, the player lights additional torches revealing a massive mural.

The mural shows the truth behind the civilization:

Individuals labeled as “unworthy” being sacrificed

Their energy flowing into Thoth

Thoth growing stronger as knowledge and souls accumulate

Robert finally understands that the civilization’s prosperity was maintained through systematic sacrifice.

Thoth reveals the truth:

The system was designed to harvest intellectual energy.

Final Confrontation

Robert reaches the altar chamber where the Scribe stands.

A boss encounter begins.

The Scribe attacks while Robert uses his abilities to survive:

Barrier to block attacks

Offensive symbol ability to damage the Scribe

Each successful attack removes portions of the Scribe’s health.

Cultists watch from below but do not intervene.

The altar resembles a balcony overlooking the ritual chamber.



 

The Fall of the Civilization 

Over time, the civilization reached intellectual stagnation. Breakthroughs ceased. Energy flow slowed. The paradise decayed. 

Now only a small cult remains descendants continuing sacrifices to revive the golden age, unaware they are merely sustaining Thoth’s emergence. 

Confronting the Cult 

The protagonist enters a ritual chamber filled with blood, artifacts of victims, and carved names. 

The Scribe declares: 'We preserve the worthy. We remove the noise.' 

Using powers granted by Thoth, the protagonist executes the Scribe and the cultists, believing he is freeing sacrificed souls. 

Instead, the mass release of stored energy transfers directly to Thoth. The cult was not only worshippers  they were containment. Because he is using Thoth’s powers, he is considered scribe and because of that the energy is transfered to Thoth. 



Exiting the Pyramid 

As he exits, the sky darkens. A vast ibis-like silhouette forms in the clouds. 

Back in his apartment, he looks through the window. The presence is real. Physical. 

By dismantling the cult, he removed the final anchor. He freed the god who engineered the system. 

Thematic Conclusion 

The protagonist believed hierarchy was necessary. By violently replacing the Scribe and enforcing his own correction, he unknowingly became the Apex  even if only briefly. 

The cult was consistent. Thoth was ideological. The protagonist was arrogant. The player believed they did good  until the sky darkened. 

 

